      </li>
      <li class="mb-2">
        <strong>Eesley, C.; Wang, Y. 2017.</strong> Social Influence in Entrepreneurial Career Choice: Evidence from Randomized Field Experiments on Entrepreneurial Mentorship. <em>Research Policy</em>, 46(3), 636&ndash;650. Randomized field evidence that structured peer mentorship measurably increases entrepreneurial activity among engineering students.
      </li>
      <li class="mb-2">
        <strong>Eesley, C.; Hsu, D.; Roberts, E.B. 2014.</strong> The Contingent Effects of Top Management Teams on Venture Performance. <em>Strategic Management Journal</em>, 35(12), 1798&ndash;1817.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Lee, Y.S.; Eesley, C. 2021.</strong> Do University Entrepreneurship Programs Promote Entrepreneurship? <em>Strategic Management Journal</em>, 42(4), 833&ndash;861.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-4">
      See also the <strong>Stanford E145</strong> course (taught since 2009; <a class="link" href="/teaching">Teaching</a>), recently re-anchored on the <a class="link" href="https://www.engineeringchallenges.org/challenges.aspx" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NAE Grand Challenges for Engineering</a>, which puts the same institutional argument into undergraduate engineering practice.
    </p>
